MPcs characteristically show a single maximum Q band, unlike metal free Pcs which have split Q band, in the near-infrared region of the UV–Vis spectrum (Q band maxima are shown in Table 1
                        ) and a relatively lower absorption in the blue-region, B band, Fig. 1
                        A. The metalation of the H2Pc to form complex 1 was confirmed by UV-vis spectroscopy where the two Q bands collapsed into one on metalation, Fig. 1A. In addition to structural characterisation, the solubility of 5 in water, unlike 4, also confirmed the presence of cationic charges on the structure of the compound. Fig. 1B shows the spectra of 4 and 5 in DMSO and complex 5 in water. Complex 5 is aggregated in DMSO and more so in water. Aggregation is typical of phthalocyanines in aqueous media [41]. Aggregation in Pcs is judged by the presence of broad or split Q bands, with the low energy band being due to the aggregate and the high energy band due to the monomer [41].
